results.name: Differences of consecutive powerful numbers (definition 1).
comment: The term 1 appears infinitely often. Erdos conjectured that two consecutive 1's do not occur. (see Guy).
reference: R. K. Guy, Unsolved Problems in Number Theory, B16
link: Reinhard Zumkeller, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, Powerful numbers
example: The first two powerful numbers are 1 and 4, there difference is 3, so a(1)=3.
results.author: _Jud McCranie_, Oct 15 2002
